# The Blueprint 📐

Just like other OOP languages, C# uses classes.

```csharp
public class Car {
    public string color = "Red";
}

// Usage
Car myCar = new Car();
Console.WriteLine(myCar.color);
```

# Getters and Setters 🛡️

No need to write `GetX()` and `SetX()` methods. Use Properties!

```csharp
class Person {
    private string name; // Field

    public string Name { // Property
        get { return name; }
        set { name = value; }
    }
}
// Usage:
p.Name = "Bob"; // Calls 'set'
Console.WriteLine(p.Name); // Calls 'get'
```

# The Magic Syntax ✨

If you don't need special logic in get/set, just do this:

```csharp
public class Person {
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }
}
```
Compiler creates the private backing fields automatically!

# Building Objects 🏗️

Same name as class, no return type.

```csharp
public class Box {
    public int Size { get; set; }

    // Constructor
    public Box(int size) {
        Size = size;
    }
}

Box b = new Box(10);
```

